Thinking Constitution Engine — Project Context (Canonical) — v0.5 Patch

Scope of patch: Adds Uncertainty Semantics + Constitutional Overrides.
Non-goals remain: no Bayesian updating, no utility maximization, no autonomous execution, no belief revision without review.

6.5 Uncertainty Semantics (NEW in v0.5)
Why this exists

v0.4 requires uncertainty, but v0.5 defines what uncertainty does mechanically.

The kernel treats uncertainty as a first-class governance constraint:

Uncertainty does not “resolve itself”

Uncertainty constrains action eligibility and intensity

Uncertainty must be declared, auditable, and reviewable

Representation (kernel-level, non-probabilistic)

The kernel supports uncertainty as bounded or ordinal—not necessarily probabilistic.

Allowed kernel encodings

Ordinal: UncertaintyLevel ∈ {LOW, MED, HIGH, UNKNOWN}

Bounded interval (optional): UncertaintyBand = [low, high] on a normalized 0–1 scale
(This is a container, not a commitment to Bayesian semantics.)

Rule: every information artifact that can influence action must carry:

confidence (how strongly held)

uncertainty (how fragile/underspecified)

provenance (Evidence linkage)

Uncertainty’s mechanical effect: Proportionate Action Gating

The kernel enforces “Proportionate Action” through gates—not by scoring.

Each Option declares:

impact ∈ {LOW, MED, HIGH}

reversibility ∈ {HIGH, MED, LOW}

uncertainty ∈ {LOW, MED, HIGH, UNKNOWN}

dependencies (artifact IDs: observations, assumptions, interpretations)

The engine classifies allowable action intensity:

ActionClass ∈ {PROBE, LIMITED, COMMIT}

PROBE: reversible, low-stakes information-seeking actions

LIMITED: partial commitment, bounded exposure

COMMIT: high commitment / high impact actions

Gate Rule (canonical)
Let riskiness = f(impact, reversibility) where:

higher impact increases riskiness

lower reversibility increases riskiness

Then:

If riskiness is HIGH, uncertainty must be LOW (or only PROBE allowed)

If riskiness is MED, uncertainty must be ≤ MED (or LIMITED/PROBE only)

If riskiness is LOW, any uncertainty is allowed (but must be declared)

Constitutional invariant:

No Recommendation may include COMMIT-class actions unless the uncertainty gate is satisfied and the Orientation risk posture permits it.

Required uncertainty explanations

Every Recommendation must include:

uncertainty_summary (what is uncertain and why)

key_assumptions (IDs + confidence/uncertainty)

proportionate_action_justification (why intensity matches uncertainty and reversibility)

7.5 Constitutional Overrides (NEW in v0.5)
Purpose

The kernel is advisory by default. But real-world use will demand exceptions.
v0.5 adds a formal override mechanism so exceptions do not become silent drift.

Overrides are:

explicit

episode-scoped

auditable

review-mandatory

Governance Mode

The engine introduces a declared governance mode in Orientation:

GovernanceMode ∈

ADVISORY_ONLY (default)

EXTENDED_ALLOWED (explicit opt-in, scoped, logged)

Override structure

If EXTENDED_ALLOWED, Orientation must provide:

override_scope: a bounded set of permissions (not “anything”)

examples:

ALLOW_EXTERNAL_MODEL_STATE_UPDATE (adapter may update a ModelState artifact)

ALLOW_SCORING_RANKING (application may attach ranking metadata)

ALLOW_AUTO_EXECUTE_CLASS_PROBE (external executor may run PROBE actions)

override_rationale: why this exception is necessary

override_constraints: extra guardrails (e.g., “only PROBE”, “max exposure”, “time window”)

override_expiry: episode-level expiry (always ends with the episode)

Constitutional invariant:

An override cannot expand action intensity beyond what Proportionate Action gating permits unless the override explicitly declares the expansion and a ReviewRecord is mandatory.

Mandatory review on override usage

If any override is used:

A ReviewRecord must include:

what was overridden

why it was invoked

observed outcome

whether the override should be allowed again (and under what narrower scope)

Kernel non-goal preserved:
The kernel still does not silently revise beliefs or self-modify. Overrides create auditable exceptions, not hidden evolution.

